Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 40

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Question 13: Suppose the company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4. Write the code to find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer. (2 marks)¶

In [52]:
# Use the ratings dataframe made earlier (See Question 12.3)
# ratings dataframe has all 'Not given' ratings removed


# Group by restaurant name and count the rating column
rates = ratings.groupby('restaurant_name', as_index=False)['rating'].count()

# Next, subset only those rows with a rating count greater than 50
rates = rates[rates['rating']>50]

# Extract the restaurant names as a list to be used later in the code
rlist = rates['restaurant_name'].tolist()

# Group the dataframe by restaurant names and find the mean of all ratings
means = ratings.groupby('restaurant_name', as_index=False)['rating'].mean()

# Subset only the entries where the mean of rating is greater than 4
means = means[means['rating']>4]

# Select only the 4 restaurants that have greater than 50 ratings, and sort in descending order
means[means['restaurant_name'].isin(rlist)].sort_values('rating', ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)

Question 14: Suppose the company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Write the code to find the net revenue generated on all the orders given in the dataset. (2 marks)¶

In [53]:
# Find net revenue when (1) every order over $5 generates 15% profit, and (2) every order over $20 gets 25% profit

# create a function named f that returns the profit based on the conditions
def f(x):
    if x > 20:
        return x*.25  # 25% when >20
    elif x >5:
        return x*.15  # 15% when >5
    else:
        return 0      # no charge if under $5

# Apply the function to the costs column and save   
charge = df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(f)

# Add up the charges to find the total
charge.sum()
Out[53]:
6166.303

Q14 Observations:¶

  • From these 1898 orders, a net profit of $6166.30 was made

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: Write the conclusions and business recommendations derived from the analysis. (5 marks)¶

Insights:¶

Notable Trends¶
  • Half of all restaurants have 3 orders or less
  • Only 10% of restaurants have more than 25 orders
  • American cuisine is by far the most popular cuisine type, followed by Japanese
  • So far, ratings given to orders doesn't seem related to any of the factors in this dataset, not even delivery time
  • Orders are generally faster on weekends
Revenue Trends¶
  • The company generated over \$6000 in revenue from about 2000 orders
  • There is more than double the orders placed on weekends
  • Only 29% of orders were over \$20
  • The average order cost is \$16.50, and it isn't affected by day of the week
  • The order with the highest cost was $35.41
    • It seems like most food orders serve 1 to 2 people
Recommendations¶
  • More revenue can be captured if we can increase orders placed on weekdays
    • More drivers on the road during the week
    • Send reminders to customers who have never ordered during the middle of the week
    • Offer discounts on the slowest days of the week
  • More revenue can be captured if we can increase the average cost per order
    • Suggest add-on menu items during the ordering process
    • Entice customers in the app to try new restaurants that have higher ticket items
    • Offer free delivery or other perks for orders over a certain amount
    • Promote "Party Trays", "Family Meals", or office lunch catering deals
  • More revenue can be captured if we increase all orders on the app
    • Smaller charges to restaurants who refer more customers from their website to join the app
    • Customer referral bonuses (friends bring in more friends)
    • Rotating specials for repeat customers (keep them coming back)
    • Better marketing
      • Branding on driver vehicles
      • Recruit more restaurants to join the app
      • Increase app visibility by asking more customers to rate the app and leave feedback
    • Find out if there is a pattern across one-time customers
  • Collect more data, explore more trends, and test more ideas
Questions for further consideration¶
  • How can the customer base be categorized?
  • Which restaurants have the most one-time customers?
  • Which restaurants have the highest returning customers?
  • Which customers have placed the most orders?
    • Of those "FoodHub Fans", do they share any similarities?
    • Do they spend more or less than the average customer?
    • Do they all order from a common shared restaurant?
    • Could they be easily enticed with additional offers?
  • What about customers who have only ever ordered once on the app?
    • How many are there?
    • How much are their orders compared to the averages?
    • Did they give bad ratings?
    • Was the wait time long?
    • Are most one-time users ordering on a certain day of the week?
  • What's the average sale across all restaurants?
    • Which restraurants have the highest/lowest average sales?
    • What about across weekend vs weekday?

  • Which restaurants have the shortest/longest prep times?

    • Does prep time correlate with other factors, such as
      • most orders
      • highest cost
      • day of the week
